Either way, nope.

The party found a baby mimic posing as a small jewelry box.  The druid wanted to adopt it, the wizard was amused, and the thief was pissed because it kept biting her fingers.  A 'random' quest on the job board was enough justification for the thief to turn in the mimic for parts.

Walked outside to 70F and 99% humidity.  It's like being an extra in Ghost Busters: the moment you step out the door, you're slimed and can't wait to get it off.
In my house, it's more likely I'll be handing Wife0 something she hadn't realized she needed yet.
@TimMedin It sounds better if you take the title "Worlds Penultimate Hacker".  Still means second best, but no one is going to admit to not knowing that.

AI doesn't endanger Democracy.

Bad people doing bad things, with or without AI, is what endangers Democracy.

Major: Computer Information Management (BS)
Minor: Life.  Not life sciences, just life.
Job: Principal Program Manager, University and Partner Research (R7)

Last night I stretched and groaned and thought out loud, "Gaaah, it's only Tuesday."

Then I stopped to wonder, "It is Tuesday, isn't it?"

I've been using the Exhaustion rules to add some weight and urgency to my player's situations in my D&D campaign.  

"You've been moving since dawn yesterday, and fought many battles.  You feel exhaustion dogging you, tripping you, trying to pull you down." (2 levels exhaustion)
@dbelson Yes, it does.  Resist the temptation to add fuel to the flames!
@rik_ferguson As long as my Kindle doesn't go offline, I'm good.

@jaysonstreet It only works until you run out of things to print.

:-)
@lmacvittie Turning, yes.  In the right direction?  Unknown.

Oooh, I'd forgotten how bad the Twitter web client is.

Do you have stories about stupid things you've done that you'll take to your grave?

Me neither.

@jaysonstreet Just remember, Harry refused and continues to refuse to accept the curse.

The downside of fixin' ribs for my gaming group is rib fingers.  I had to draw the line when one of my players was eating over one of my books*.  

*No books were harmed in last night's episode.  No such claim can be made for the players.
I host a Friday night D&D session, and last night I realized it's cheaper to buy two racks of ribs and a ready made salad from Costco than it is to order pizza.  Ribs going on the smoker now.
I need to stop using the term 'performative art' in meetings.
RT @SecBarbie: Most security organizations are trying to build skyscrapers without first checking the foundation or learning math.

I logged into Twitter for the first time in months, expecting it to be a dumpster fire.  Instead I saw many of the people I used to enjoy reading still active and didn't think it was that bad.

Then the ads started, and the suggested topics, and the site itself, and ...
Hope to see everyone in Vegas next week!  And while you're there, stop by to see Spencer give Metasploit demonstrations.

I have the Bird and Mastodon access on my phone.  I never accessed my Mastodon anywhere other than my personal desktop and removed the Bird from my phone last year.  

I need them when traveling, we'll see if I keep AndStatus installed after this week.
Sometimes life looks you in the eye and calmly says, "Fuck you."
@SteveD3 I am now.  Thanks for asking.

Oooh, the CFP for BSides Cambridge is now open!  I need an excuse to visit Boston.

https://t.co/eLCGa38ogm

@halvarflake I'm less concerned with AI killing us all and more concerned about AI being fundamentally corrupted into a tool of politics and indoctrination.  

But that's just me.

@LitMoose I love it when my morning commute counts as zone minutes.

Yes FitBit, that's called a near miss in rush hour traffic.
Wait, why is someone retweeting a thread I was part of 7 years ago?
I'm thankful to be home and not at RSA this week.  But I also miss the chance to meet old friends and make new ones.
Raise your hand if you're not going to RSA 2023 and are happy about it.
@jpierini You can go home and sleep in your own bed at night when attending the conference.  It makes a difference.

@PaulWGeorge_ It's a great conference to meet people and learn about the breadth of products in our industry.  Spend more time talking to people than listening to the speakers.  Drink lots, sleep lots, and have fun.  

But, again, COVID.
@PaulWGeorge_ COVID.  Seriously.

I hung out with a bunch of great people today at @BSidesTampa !!!!

That is all.

Last year on this day, Snyk published an essay my daughter and I wrote together about her coming out as trans.

https://t.co/PiqZyUnDNT
@arawnsley See if there are any BSides events in your area.  Lockpick village at a BSides is always a great place to take kids, but some events have classes or presentations for younger audiences.

@BrianHonan @dildog I read a lot of bad LITRPG books, it helps me unwind at the end of the day.  

I have a park behind my house, so a walk under the oaks with a book on tape playing is another alternative.

Who's going to be at BSides Tampa this Saturday?

My daughter may be there with me, if I can get her up at 6am.  Otherwise, I'll have a spare ticket.  

https://t.co/0jiUDrGtq2

"Are you going to RSA this year?"

"Not just no, but hell no!  I'm not keen on getting COVID.  Again."
@imaguid Just like most businesses, people are willing to 'accept the risk', without actually understanding the risk.

Who's planning to be at BSidesTampa next Saturday?  I'll be attending with my daughter, if she can survive a 6am wake up call.

https://t.co/ftpujREDLZ

I have a new role!  As of Monday, I joined @Rapid7 as the <deep breath> Sr. Program Manager, Security Sciences Research Governance.  

I will be primarily focused on the Cyber Threat Intelligence Lab at USF in Tampa.   https://t.co/fA4q8UyLVJ

"Dad, you have to invest all your money in gold!!"

"Me?  I haven't been in charge of our finances in over a decade.  I have an allowance, dude."

I finally reached a major goal I've been pursuing for 7 years:  I'm below 265lbs (120 kilos) for the first time in many years.  

My next goal is to lose another 15lbs.  Maybe by the end of this year.

One of the good things about the new Twitter is it doesn't work with any of my preferred apps on my phone.  Which means it doesn't work for me.  Which means I no longer feel the need to share my thoughts any time other than when I'm at my desk.
Oh yay.  Found a full can of dark oak stain that was no longer full.  It rusted through and leaked across three shelves in the garage.

Why is he doing everything possible to drive people away from his own platform?
I still have a badly beaten copy of the first edition of Runequest.  And the second, I think.

I hadn't realized Chaosium was still around.  I remember visiting their office in the early 80's, a friend of mine was dropping off content for a module or something.  They looked remarkably like any other office of the time, not much cool stuff decorating the desks.
@snipeyhead At least a shit show is still a show.

I think I'm done buying books from Wizards of the Coast.  They can take their OGL 1.1 and shove it.

I don't need D&D One or even 5.0, I'm more than happy to go back to 3.5, and have other systems I haven't played in years that could easily take the place all my 5.0 books.

@magen_wu I have four decades of books on my shelves.  I'm sure I can find something playable without ever buying another book.

We should game together some time.
People in Florida are so funny.  It dips below 70F and suddenly there are people everywhere in parkas and Uggs boots.
@SecBarbie Next time you're in town, we'll talk over drinks about what it's like growing up with a parent who's a narcissist.

I was sipping my coffee this morning when a sneeze surprised me.  

Having hot coffee dripping out your nose is not a comfortable experience.

My second cup of coffee disappears much too quickly.
I find it easier and easier to ignore social media as time goes by.

Merry Christmas all!

We picked up a pair of penny whistles for our grown children this summer when we were in Dublin.

This is a new hell of our own making.

It's a great time to sign out of all the social media accounts for a few days.

Let's see if I can follow my own advice.

I've been having some problems with 3D printing in my garage.  It finally struck me that this is the first time since we moved to this house that the garage is below 70F.  

Still adjusting to Florida.

My efforts to lose weight are hereby paused until further notice.

Or until the baked goods run out, whichever comes first.
I can't tell if the reduced responses to my tweets are the widely discussed shadow bans by Twitter, a side-effect of many people leaving Twitter for a pachyderm, or simply the holiday season.

RT @blackgirlbytes: I've applied to enough CFPs now I think. 

But, I just remembered my manager suggested that I do more keynotes, so if y‚Ä¶
"No, when you eat all the smallest chocolate chip cookies, it is not considered 'culling the weak'."

I volunteered to pick up a few things so Wife0 could spend time backing instead.

Boy, was that a mistake.  I'm going into hiding again.

3D Print Pics: I love how this mini turned out.  

Even before I'd printed him, I had a story of this troll elder watching over the party as they make camp.  He waits until they notice him to see how they react. https://t.co/G7ejWZcr5Z

Around March, I expect Twitter to be sold for a pittance.

The new owners will appear much more reasonable at first, but there goal will still be to monetize and manipulate the audience.

So, basically more of the same.
Love this team and the work the do!

Despite the efforts by some loon, I hope people can find me as 'McKeay' on the https://t.co/CJc7wX2FhY Mastodon server.

I think bots will be more inconvenienced by this move than humans.
I plan on being at the post office tomorrow at 8am to send off my last two packages.  I needed this weekend to put the finishing touches on the gifts.

Wife0 decided she didn't like how I was labeling boxes for shipping so she took over.  

I wasn't doing it wrong, I just wasn't doing it 'properly'.

The annual sacrifice to the gods of merchants has  been deemed acceptable and the blessings of the pine tree has been bestowed upon our family.

3D Print Pics: Printing articulated dragons to give away this Christmas.  I found a filament that comes out polychromatic, a shift of red, blue, and yellow that changes depending how the light hits it. https://t.co/Z0PzRngy7X

@akanygren The model is an articulated dragon by McGyBeer.  You can find it on most model platforms.

The filament is OVV3D Tri-color (Red/Blue/Yellow)  I printed it at 125% of base size on my Prusa i3 mk3.
@lil_lost I was a little disappointed when I first opened this spool of filament.  I had NO idea it would turn into the beauty you see in the picture.

Any leftovers in the fridge are fair game on the second day after being cooked.  

That's an important rule to remember this weekend.
Has anyone started publishing their 2023 security predictions yet?
@atluxity You think I'd remember?
We've never seen a real, living pink flamingo in the wild here in Florida.  But now we've seen a Roseinated Spoonbill. https://t.co/ZVlmTSmHNd
Yesterday, the alligators all hid because of the rain.  Today we got to see alligators, turtles, manatees, and more.  There are two manatees and an alligator in this picture.

The Social Media Death-spiral, from Dork Tower.  

https://t.co/6H7GOXjhPN
Life is too short for bad coffee.
I brought my father and Spawn0 to #BsidesOrlando and we're teaching Martin the Eldest to pick locks in the Lockpick Village. https://t.co/734IHWYJFt
@krypt3ia @SteveD3 Santa Barbarian needs a lot of work, but I have time to spare at the moment.
The view from my backdoor this morning. He flew away moments later. https://t.co/hNoEwLCIA0
If I can convince my father to go to #BSidesOrlando with me this weekend, we can have three generations of my family represented: Martin I, Martin II & Martin III
@corq @Wawa Waving from west of Orlando as you drive by.
@SteveD3 @krypt3ia I got my Banksy photos hung up earlier this week.  Got three in England, the fourth in New Orleans.  None of the Doctor's work though. https://t.co/jGVbyg3Qd0
RT @EffinBirds: https://t.co/YPMjGDoLmc

@gisellis @Beaker Obsession is not a problem by itself.  

But you are creeping right up to the edge, especially if anyone else needs counter space.

@akanygren @tweethue Busy printing N-scale buildings for a Christmas village for Wife0.  Unluckily, we have very little to compare the buildings to for scale, so at least a few of them will need a second print to adjust the scale.
3D Print Pic: She is the chief of a tribe of gnolls, he is their high priest.  They hate each other, but not nearly as much as they hate the  player characters. https://t.co/45AIBLYABt

Both my Prusa printers are essentially stock builds, or were until this morning.  I replaced the hotend on the Mini with a Copperhead from Slice Engineering.

So far, getting much better results, no stringing at all.  Yay!

@MisterGlass I had some clogging problems with one PLA roll, but switching to a different filament fixed that issue.  My biggest issue has been stringing, which seems a lot better with the Copperhead.

@MisterGlass Slice has a 'Prusa Mini Upgrade kit'.  I got the cheapest kit, just the hot end replacement. Took an hour to do, 

The hot end is a known weakness of the Mini.

I think printing and painting minis is an adult version of playing with dolls.

Or maybe that's just me.

3D Print Pics: This lizardman is hanging out in the trees, waiting for the head of a PC to come into sight.  Printed almost two years ago, he now has the coloration to hide in the forest. https://t.co/TI1yIBG6eD
3D Print Pics: A pair of summoned fire elementals.  Printed with a clear red resin and brushed with a metallic wax.  Haven't decided if I'll paint over the stone base yet. https://t.co/JAoylnEmmk

@gisellis I needed some way to highlight the figures without obscuring the translucent resin.  

I might try some water elementals in blue resin and highlighted with silver wax soon.

This is not a parody account. 

At least not intentionally.

Glad for the extra hour today.  It let me get the family organized for the Orlando Maker Faire much easier this morning.

#OrlandoMakerFaire

Just found a 6 port hub as well!

I've got some really old junk in my drawers.

I just found a 10/100 8 port hub in one of my drawers. 

Can you even buy hubs anymore?

I was in the garage and found not one, but two Alesis compressor/limiter/gate audio devices.  

I did so much harm to the audio of my podcast, using their functions poorly.
@AlbertoCairo That reminds me, today is the last day of early voting in FL.  I have my afternoon planned around it.
Elon Musk is the physical incarnation of the Twitter Fail Whale.

The latest Something Positive captures the feeling of November 1st perfectly!

https://t.co/VBIjHv6hJf

@krypt3ia Hear, yes.

But it's not like anyone listens as we scream into the void.
@csoandy "Oh god, he's at it again!" is a pretty common phrase, at least amongst the people who know you.
How do we have candy left over this morning?
Florida Halloweens are great.  Until the mosquitos come out and decide they want a snack too.
@dimitrimckay I don't see a problem.

I have tickets for the family to #MakerFaireOrlando this weekend.  We have been to half a dozen Maker Faire's, starting with the very first one.  Exciting to get another opportunity to see the creativity on display.

3D Print Pic: I'm not sure why, but Wife0 has been very insistent that I need horns for Halloween.  What is she trying to tell me?

In the front is a set of horns that fade from gold to red.  In background is a half mask skull with a single horn. https://t.co/RX2J4ZfaII
@gattaca How can you tell with a cat?

3D Print Pic: I printed this Potion of Fire Breathing in translucent red resin over a year ago. Last night I buffed on some gold luster wax to finish it.  It stands just under 4"/10cm, and I've got both smaller and larger versions. https://t.co/8sHon0wPKL

Wife0 has me printing n-scale buildings for her Christmas train setup.  

I wonder if I can sneak a group of adventurers into the setup, along with some snow elementals for them to fight.
@krypt3ia I'm going with Santa Barbarian this year.

Found a spool of PLA labeled 'Bone White' that I opened two years ago.  It's been packed in a 1 gallon bag with desiccant, inside a sealed box with more desiccant, so it should be fine to print more dragons with.

3D Print Pic: A trio of Bone Dragons hanging out with their friend, the mimic.

The tan Dragons were printed using a wood fill PLA, but that soon was really stringy.  They're still shedding, but lost a lot of hair to a heat gun. https://t.co/poeZTN6Ufu

I kept seeing messages from #MakerFaireOrlando in my Instagram feed and panicked at the thought I might have missed it!

Fortunately, it's actually in two weeks and there are still tickets left.

Today's project is printing a flexible Bone Dragon.  I pulled a spool of wood-like PLA filament I hadn't used in ~3 years, which led me to wonder how long properly stored PLA can last.  

15 years, if properly stored with desiccant, away from sunlight.  https://t.co/a3PpUASGVi.
@k8em0 I never felt I was your equal, @k8em0 :-)

"All I need to do know is clean up the last supports and get the blood off of it."

The joys of 3D printing and removing supports from a large model.
@danielkennedy74 Something evil that arose from the pumpkin patch!
Wife0 returns from her three week trip to Italy this afternoon.  I am in the process of hiding the evidence, also known as 'cleaning house'.

Well,  that was surprisingly easy.

My Synology 214+ lost a drive recently.  The hardest part of replacing the drive was getting the ^&()&#$! thing to close up properly,  which took more time than the rest of the replacement process combined.
Overheard: "You know the praying mantis cuts off the head of her mate and eats it afterwards.  That's what I did with all mine."

I put in lighting in my cabinets over the weekend.  Wireless, rechargeable lights are cheap to install and are controlled by remote.  And yes, I have a shelf dedicated to chests and mimics. https://t.co/PWYniiahau
@lmacvittie I'm running a campaign where I'm using traditional enemies with a twist.  Right now the PCs are in a forest being stalked by a goblin ranger who uses terrain and simple traps to vex them.
I had to go sit on the porch.  My children are trying to remember how to play the ocarina. They're 21 & 23.
RT @mfratto: Oh my god. I never met Kevin in person but we talked on Twitter and I was always impressed with his range of activities and wi‚Ä¶
RT @SexCigarsBooze: NOPE, NOT UNTIL I GET #COFFEE ... https://t.co/LuKPU2BVdj

3D Print Pic: This Horned Devil was one of my first big prints, now zenithal primed.  I actually bled several times while putting him together, all those pointy bits are really sharp. https://t.co/LZv6soDcoI
3D Print Pic: This is the Storm Giant Prince, if I remember right.  I love the pattern on the sword.  He's about 7in/175mm tall.  Another example of zenithal priming https://t.co/H6mwPR7FLI
Home again after a quick round trip to DC.  I drove 28 over 3 days. No major damage to my neighborhood, as far as I can tell.  Just got confirmation Wife0 arrived at her destination in Italy.
@mfratto I did not stop south of the border. But I did stop to see Jack in Georgia.

Wife0 thought I drove her to DC so she could make her flight to Italy.

The reality is, I was just looking for an excuse to visit with @jack_daniel

Long day driving from Orlando to DC.  Wife0 needs to be here for her long awaited trip to Italy. I will head south tomorrow. I hope my kids survive Ian without us.

They're 21 & 23, and not completely helpless.  Unless the Internet goes down.

3D print pics: A for Fire Giant I printed last year, reprimed.  Need to work on my lighting and photo setup.  He won't be an enemy for quite some time, if ever. But still fun to have if I need to scare the players. https://t.co/zp7tVoxolM

Looks like a road trip to DC tomorrow. Her flight is at 2pm tomorrow and is likely to be cancelled.

Her destination is Italy, the weeks with her parents and siblings.  We're not going to let a hurricane stop her adventure.

3D Print Pics: The continuing saga of 'zenethal highlighting'.  Yes, there's a name for the method I'm using.  

Today's print is a displacer hyena, base coat of black, heavy overlay of army green.  

https://t.co/vS6aR4XO6N
I'm hoping Ian will have run out of energy by Wednesday, but who knows.

Working on a project where I've printed every part 3-5+ times.  First attempt was too small, then problems with supports, and several different tests. 

I think I've got it now.

@ChrisJohnRiley More curiosity than patience.  One of my attempts was to print the figure in PLA, but several of the important parts were to fragile.  I want to try different things to see what worked best.
I just discovered Chitubox  exports files for Anycubic printers again.  Best software I've found for adding supports, though a lot of people claim the Prusa slicer works equally well.

@gattaca @InfoSec_World Wife0 is supposed to be in DC Wednesday night, flying to Italy the next day.  She's asked me if I'd be willing to drive her if weather is too bad.  

Was hoping to see you, but you have a good excuse.

3D print pic: A six inch tall forest dragon I printed a while ago. Another of my experiments, black base coat of primer, a wet coat of the black, followed quickly by a coat of oak brown.  Almost looks like carved wood, appropriate for this woodland guardian. https://t.co/mlnAWckuxC
3D print pic:. The Goblin King and his attendants. Another experiment with overlaying coats of primer in two colors. https://t.co/0jaaHu2Zd9
@Timm4h The goblins are a fractious race, prone to hyperbole. They have many kings, who seldom love long lives.
@pmhesse It is resin. Spraying a lighter primer over a still wet base coat gives them some extra depth. Looks good until I decide to paint more details.

You are correct, there were people active in security much earlier than the 90's.  But it wasn't a career path, something you could plan to get into like you can now.  There's a difference between people forging a path, like Donn Parker and people looking for a path to follow.

When someone asks, 'How do I get a job like yours?' there's not an answer I can give them. I made a series of decisions that seemed minor at the time but had a major impact on my career over time.  Those opportunities no longer exist.  You have to find your own path.

5/5 Fin

I saw a treasure trove of data my former employer was doing nothing with and decided it was something I had to dive into and make something of.

Now I have friends at every level of the security community, mostly just by being an authentic person. 

4/n

I started podcasting with a cheap desktop mic because there was only one podcast on security.

I interviewed close to 500 people over the course of the podcast, and made contacts that changed the entire course of my career.

3/n

Security wasn't a separate discipline yet in the 90s, but I found it interesting and did what I could.

I started a blog about security because I wanted to learn HTML and Linux skills before there were any platforms to make it easy.

2/n

"How can I get a job like yours?" is a very complex question for me.  There isn't a path, I've had to create one that's unique to me.  I've made so many mistakes, but I've also been very lucky in making the right decisions that only made sense in hindsight.  1/n

@PhantomSpaceCop I use Elegoo water washable resin almost exclusively.  But it's brittle and will break if anything is dropped.  There are more elastic resins, but you're back to using IPA at that point.

@PhantomSpaceCop Rather than paper towels, look at Scot Shop Towels.  A box isn't that expensive and I haven't quite made it through a full one yet.  If you see white spots on your cured prints, it's a sign they weren't clean enough, use a toothbrush on the figures before curing.
@PhantomSpaceCop BTW, you're going to get resin in all sorts of unexpected places, there's no way to avoid it.  Get some mats to put down on your surface so you can prevent the worst accidents.
@PhantomSpaceCop Cheap silicon mats you can lay down anywhere, the bigger the better.  Mine are 12x24 and I wish I'd gotten bigger.
